english:
  title: Cold Food Festival on the Road
  author: Choi Suk-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last year at Cold Food Festival on the Chang'an road,
    I collapsed drunk amid the fragrance of a hundred flowers.
    This year at Cold Food Festival in the borderland fortress,
    Whispered winds and rain follow the marching banners.

    Year after year the seasons turn and return,
    Yet a soldier's path is written by fate alone.
    At dusk on the frontier, the smoke of hearths grows thin,
    And lonely willows in a distant village tremble in spring rain.

    By Dragon Bay on the river I raise a single cup,
    Waiting—will word of apricot blossoms come or not?
    The landscape remains unchanged, yet my temples have turned gray,
    Where will I wait for you again when next year comes?
  footnotes:
    - 'Cold Food Festival (寒食): A traditional spring festival held a day or two before Qingming, when only cold food was eaten. The poem uses it as a temporal marker, comparing the speaker''s experience at the festival in two different years.'
    - 'Chang''an: The ancient capital of China, here representing the speaker''s peaceful past.'
    - 'Dragon Bay (龍灣): Likely a specific location in the borderlands, or possibly a poetic name for a scenic river bend.'
    - 'Apricot blossoms: A traditional symbol in Chinese poetry for spring beauty and renewal, but here tinged with melancholy waiting and uncertainty.'
